Project Overview

This project focuses on estimating the tire-road friction coefficient (μ) using Kalman Filter based observer design in MATLAB.

The friction coefficient is one of the most important parameters in vehicle braking systems because it determines the available tire grip between the road and the tire. It directly affects the performance of systems such as:

ABS (Anti-lock Braking System)
ESC (Electronic Stability Control)
Traction Control
Autonomous Emergency Braking

Since the friction coefficient cannot be directly measured using a physical sensor, it must be estimated using vehicle measurements and mathematical models.

This project was developed in two phases:

Phase 1: Speed-based friction estimation
Phase 2: Acceleration-based friction estimation

The second phase improves estimation robustness by addressing observability limitations found in the first model.

Objective

To design a state-space observer using a Kalman Filter for estimating the tire-road friction coefficient under noisy sensor conditions.

Phase 1: Speed-Based Friction Estimation
Theory

The vehicle braking model is based on:

dv/dt = -μg

Where:

v = vehicle speed
μ = friction coefficient
g = gravitational acceleration

The state vector is defined as:

x = [v
μ]

where:

vehicle speed is measured
friction coefficient is estimated

Gaussian sensor noise is added to simulate realistic speed measurements.

A Kalman Filter is designed to estimate both speed and friction coefficient from noisy measurements.

Observation

The initial speed-based model showed estimation drift near zero velocity due to weak observability.

As the vehicle speed approached zero, the system had limited information to accurately estimate friction coefficient.

This led to the development of Phase 2.

Phase 2: Acceleration-Based Friction Estimation
Theory

The improved model uses:

a = -μg

which gives:

μ = -a/g

Where:

a = vehicle acceleration (deceleration)

Since acceleration directly reflects tire-road friction, this model provides stronger estimation performance.

The state is simplified to:

x = [μ]

and the measurement equation becomes:

y = -gμ

where acceleration is the measured output.

A Kalman Filter is used to estimate friction coefficient using noisy acceleration sensor data.

Result

The acceleration-based model showed stable convergence of estimated friction coefficient toward the true value.

This provided significantly better observer performance compared to the speed-based model.

MATLAB Files
phase1_speed_based_estimation.m

Includes:

braking model using speed
noisy speed sensor simulation
state-space model
Kalman filter design
friction coefficient estimation
phase2_acceleration_based_estimation.m

Includes:

braking model using acceleration
noisy acceleration sensor simulation
improved observer design
Kalman filter implementation
stable friction estimation
Sample Results
Phase 1

Speed-based estimation demonstrated the concept successfully but showed estimator drift due to weak observability.

Phase 2

Acceleration-based estimation showed stable convergence of estimated friction coefficient close to the true friction value.

This made the observer significantly more robust and realistic for automotive applications.

Key Learnings
State-space system modeling
Observer design fundamentals
Kalman Filter implementation
Process noise vs measurement noise tuning
System observability limitations
Model refinement through engineering iteration
Automotive braking system estimation concepts
